<exercises><title> <em>Check your Understanding</em> </title>

	<exercise label="chkpts-examples"><title> <em>Answer-the-Following</em> </title>
	
		<task label="chkpt-examples-1"><title> <em>Understanding the Role of the Integrating Factor</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					In the examples provided, what is the primary function of the integrating factor <m>\mu(x)</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							To transform the left-hand side of the differential equation into a single derivative.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor allows us to rewrite the equation in a form that can be directly integrated.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To eliminate the derivative term completely.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The derivative remains but is rewritten in a convenient form.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To make the equation separable.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor method does not rely on separation of variables.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							To ensure that the right-hand side of the equation is always zero.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor does not necessarily eliminate the right-hand side.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-examples-2"><title> <em>Key Steps in the Solution Process</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which of the following is the correct sequence of steps when solving a first-order linear differential equation using the integrating factor method?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							Rewrite the equation in standard form, compute the integrating factor, multiply the equation by the integrating factor, integrate both sides, and solve for <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! These are the essential steps in the integrating factor method.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Find the integrating factor, multiply by it, take the second derivative, and solve for <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The second derivative is not needed in this method.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Integrate both sides first, find the integrating factor, then rewrite the equation in standard form.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor is computed before integration.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Rewrite the equation in standard form, take the square root of both sides, and integrate.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The square root step is not part of the integrating factor method.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-examples-3"><title> <em>Choosing the Correct Integrating Factor</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If a first-order linear equation is written as <m>y' + 3y = x</m>, what is the appropriate integrating factor?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>e^{\int 3dx} = e^{3x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The integrating factor is found using <m>P(x) = 3</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>e^{\int xdx} = e^{x^2/2}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor should be based on <m>P(x)</m>, not <m>Q(x)</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>e^{-3x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The exponent should be positive, following <m>\mu(x) = e^{\int P(x) dx}</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>3e^x</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The integrating factor should be based on the integral of <m>P(x)</m>, not an arbitrary function.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-examples-4"><title> <em>Final Step in Solving the Equation</em> </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Once the equation is rewritten in the form <m>\frac{d}{dx} [\mu(x)y] = \mu(x)Q(x)</m>, what is the next step?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Differentiate both sides again.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Further differentiation is not needed at this stage.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Multiply both sides by <m>\mu(x)</m> again.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The equation is already multiplied by the integrating factor.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							Integrate both sides to find <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! At this stage, integration is the key step to solving for <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Factor the equation to solve for <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The equation is already structured for integration, not factoring.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

	</exercise>

</exercises>
